No, what you are saying is that the risk of dieing from an accidental handgun death is small compared to the risk of being murdered.  But that is not the relevant statistic.  The relevant statistic is the number of accidental handgun deaths compared to the number of deaths that handguns have prevented.  And even then, it would only matter if the death was prevented in a situation where there would have been no time to get the lock off.<br>
